1. Questions to answer

This report is going to identify difference among demographic regions and find out the development of difference over time.
According to the data provided, this report will focus on three dimensions: population, income and life expectance.

3. Dataset cleaning

From the above summary, invalid values were spotted in the previous step.
It is important to clear invalid values from the dataset to reach a meaningful conslusion.

# count missing value by columns
colSums(is.na(gapminder))
##    Country       Year       life population     income     region 
##          0          0          0      25817       2341          0

There are missing values in both column population and income

# remove missing values
gapminder_cleaned <- na.omit(gapminder)
# check the new dataset, with NAs removed
head(gapminder_cleaned)

4. Analysis

4.1 Life expectance

ggplot(gapminder_cleaned, aes(x = Year, y = life, group = Country)) + 
  geom_point(aes(color = region)) + 
  ggtitle("Life Expectance by Year, colored by region") + xlab("Year") + ylab("Life Expectance (Years)")

There are 197 countries in the dataset, it is impossible to put in legend for the above plot. From the above plot, it is easy to conclude people are having significantly higher life expectance now than it was 200 years ago. Another interesting finding is that, in 1800 and 2000, the gap between countries are less than the gap in 1950. One of the possible reason is that, during 50s, some countries have signifcant development in income and technology; and it takes couple decades for such technology to spread all over the world. Therefore, the gap of life expectance among countries is narrowing.

However, there are too many countries, and the plot is not big enough.

ggplot(gapminder_cleaned, aes(x = region, y = life, fill = region)) + 
  geom_boxplot() + 
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 45)) + 
  ggtitle("Life expectance by region") + xlab("Regions") + ylab("Life Expectance (Years)")

From the above boxplot, Europe & Central Asia is having the highest life expectance in the overall time span, and South Asia and Sub-Saharan Africa are having the lowest life expectance. However, South Asia has a wider box, which mean the difference among countries are having difference life expectance.

4.2 Population

ggplot(gapminder_cleaned, aes(x = Year, y = population, group = Country)) +
  geom_point(aes(color = region)) + 
  geom_line(aes(color = region)) + 
  ggtitle("Population over time by countries, colored by region") + xlab("Year") + ylab("Population")

There are 197 countries in the dataset, it is impossible to put in legend for the above plot. The slope on the plot shows before 1950, global population was growing steadly. After 1950, population was growing faster for most of countries, especially for top 3 countries by popluation.

At the same time, the country with largest population is always the largest in population throught out the whole period of dataset. So does the seond place, and it is correct for most of time for third place. Therefore, running a sort on population of the last year in the dataset can show top countries with population. To find out top countries in population:

# subset data
yearSubset = subset(gapminder_cleaned, Year == max(gapminder_cleaned$Year))
# sort data by population
head(yearSubset[order(-yearSubset$population), ])

4.3 Income

ggplot(gapminder_cleaned, aes(x = Year, y = income, group = Country)) +
  geom_point(aes(color = region)) + 
  ggtitle("Income over time by countries, colored by region") + xlab("Year") + ylab("Income")

There are 197 countries in the dataset, it is impossible to put in legend for the above plot. However, from the above plot, it can be found that East Asia & Pacific was having huge income boost. And it looks like one country was growing extremely fast from 1950 to 1975, but its income droped after its peak. While another country was keep growing in its income, however in a slower pace than the above mentioned country. But, since there are too many countries in this plot. We need a subset of data to see if all previous founding is true; and if it is true, which two countries were making miracle.

# Subseting East Asia & Pacific Regioin
regionSubset = subset(gapminder_cleaned, region == "East Asia & Pacific")
# amount of countries in this region
length(unique(regionSubset$Country))
## [1] 27
# count missing value by columns
colSums(is.na(regionSubset))
##    Country       Year       life population     income     region 
##          0          0          0          0          0          0
ggplot(regionSubset, aes(x = Year, y = income, group = Country)) +
  geom_point(aes(color = Country)) + 
  ggtitle("Income over time in East Asia & Pacific, by countries") + xlab("Year") + ylab("Income")

From the plot above, the previous assumption was proved and those two patent belong two countries respectively.

ggplot(regionSubset, aes(x = Year, y = income, group = Country)) +
  geom_point(aes(color = Country)) + 
  ggtitle("Income over time in East Asia & Pacific, by countries") + xlab("Year") + ylab("Income") + 
  xlim(1950, max(gapminder_cleaned$Year))
## Warning: Removed 375 rows containing missing values (geom_point).

From the plot above, the patent of income growth for different coutries are more significant.

# sort data by income in 2015
regionSubset_2015 = subset(regionSubset, Year == 2015)
top10CountryList <- regionSubset_2015[order(-regionSubset_2015$income), ]$Country[1:10]
# region subset by country
regionSubset_Country = subset(regionSubset, Country %in% top10CountryList)
ggplot(regionSubset_Country, aes(x = Year, y = income, group = Country)) +
  geom_point(aes(color = Country)) + 
  ggtitle("Top 10 income over time in East Asia & Pacific, by countries") + xlab("Year") + ylab("Income") + 
  xlim(1950, max(gapminder_cleaned$Year))
## Warning: Removed 150 rows containing missing values (geom_point).

From the plot above, it is obvious that Australia had highest income for most of the time from 1950 to 2015. And Singapore grew over Australia and became the highest income among 10 countries.

5. Conclusion

In the past 200 years, the global life expectance, population and income were growing for most countries. And the growth is graduately from the big picture. However, details of growth are always varies by region and countries. For life expectance, European is always have the highest expectance. For population, China and India are always having the most population in the world. For income, the amount was not consistent through out the history. And when zooming into region, different stories may happen. Just like Austrlia, it was highest in the region but caught by Singapore at the very ending.
